timeline.message:
Introduces HttpRequestParser and HttpResponseParser

This completes the transition of HTTP instrumentation to the new HttpRequest
and HttpResponse types by implementing parsing. Notably, the new parsing
functions can be implemented by lambdas and pass a TraceContext vs scoping.

The main change is implementing parsers more simply.

Ex before:
```java
httpTracing = httpTracing.toBuilder()
    .clientParser(new HttpClientParser() {
      @Override
      public <Req> void request(HttpAdapter<Req, ?> adapter, Req req, SpanCustomizer span) {
        span.name(adapter.method(req)); // default span name
        span.tag("http.url", adapter.url(req)); // the whole url, not just the path
      }
    })
    .build();
```

Now
```java
httpTracing = httpTracing.toBuilder()
    .clientRequestParser((req, context, span) -> {
      span.name(req.method()); // default span name
      span.tag("http.url", req.url()); // the whole url, not just the path
    })
    .build();
```

This increased performance and allows easier access to extra fields. For
example, a commonly request was to add extra fields as tags. This can now
be done in the parser instead of the FinishedSpanHandler, if desired.

Ex.
```java
httpTracing = httpTracing.toBuilder()
    .clientRequestParser((req, context, span) -> {
      HttpClientRequestParser.DEFAULT.parse(req, context, span);
      String userName = ExtraFieldPropagation.get(context, "user-name");
      if (userName != null) span.tag("user-name", userName);
    })
    .build();
```

In order to not break api, all the other logic was kept in
`HttpParserAdapter`, which we can't remove until the next release.
